{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:10:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15813"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15813"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.54,0.07,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102409"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8504"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84880"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"5868"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34884"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102409"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman is an inpatient recovering from routine elective surgery. A nurse presses the emergency buzzer in her room when the patient is witnessed to start having generalised tonic-clonic movements. The junior doctor is on the ward nearby and immediately attends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is actively convulsing with generalised rhythmic jerking movements. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. The patient has no significant medical history, no known history of seizures and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxygen is given and jaw thrust is applied.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer intravenous midazolam","Place patient in a lateral position","Insert oropharyngeal airway","Request urgent computed tomography of the brain","Commence intravenous levetiracetam"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is having an acute seizure, likely precipitated by her acute illness. The immediate priority in seizure management is ensuring patient safety and protecting the airway, before considering medication administration. The standard practice in the Emergency Department setting is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApply oxygen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EJaw thrust if needed - usually patients will have trismus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuction oral cavity if any obvious secretions/airway noise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELateral position to reduce aspiration risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConsider IV/IM midazolam for termination of seizure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first four items usually happen within seconds of each other.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacing the patient in a lateral position\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step, to reduce the risk of aspiration of gastric contents. Other similar safety measures would include lowering the bed, raising side rails, removing hazards, placing a pillow under the head, and ensuring suction is available. These measures all focus on protecting the patient from injury and maintaining airway patency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature as most seizures self-terminate within 2-3 minutes. Benzodiazepines should be reserved for prolonged seizures or status epilepticus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence intravenous levetiracetam\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as a first-line agent. Second-line anticonvulsants are only indicated after failed response to two doses of benzodiazepines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest urgent computed tomography of the brain\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate later to investigate the cause but is not the priority during active seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInserting an oropharyngeal airway\u003C/strong\u003E during an active seizure risks injury to the patient and healthcare worker. Airway adjuncts should only be considered once the seizure has terminated if required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter implementing safety measures, if the seizure continues beyond 3 minutes, benzodiazepines would be indicated. If the seizure persists after two doses of benzodiazepines, second-line agents and specialist support should be sought.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most seizures self-terminate within 2-3 minutes; benzodiazepines should be withheld during this period.","Initial management of seizures focuses on patient safety and airway protection rather than medication administration.","After two doses of benzodiazepines without response, second-line anticonvulsants and specialist support are required."],"references":["Emergency Care Institute. Seizures. NSW, Australia: Agency for Clinical Innovation. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/ecat/adult/seizures","Alwaki A, Winkel D. Generalised seizures. BMJ Best Practice: BMJ Publishing Group; 2022 [cited 23 Feb 2023]. Available from: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/543","Krumholz A, Wiebe S, Gronseth GS, et al. Evidence-based guideline: Management of an unprovoked first seizure in adults. Report of the Guideline Development Subcommittee of the American Academy of Neurology and the American Epilepsy Society. 2015;84(16):1705-13. Available from: https://n.neurology.org/content/neurology/84/16/1705.full.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15813"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84880"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T11:37:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T11:37:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8504"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102409"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt"